  "prompt": "My boyfriend cheated on me. I felt betrayed and it still haunts me. How to stop thinking about it?",
  "response": "I'm really sorry you're going through this. Betrayal can be incredibly painful and it's natural for these feelings to linger. Here are some steps that might help you navigate through this difficult time:\n\n1. **Allow Yourself to Feel:** It's important to acknowledge your emotions\u2014whether it's hurt, anger, sadness, or confusion. Suppressing these feelings can make them harder to manage in the long run.\n\n2. **Reach Out for Support:** Talking to trusted friends or family members can provide comfort and perspective. Sometimes, simply sharing your feelings can alleviate some of the burden.\n\n3. **Consider Professional Help:** A therapist or counselor can offer strategies to help you process your emotions and rebuild your sense of trust and self-worth.\n\n4. **Take Care of Yourself:** Engage in activities that you enjoy and that make you feel good about yourself. This could be anything from exercising, reading, pursuing a hobby, or practicing mindfulness and meditation.\n\n5. **Set Boundaries:** If you're still in contact with your boyfriend and it's causing you pain, it might help to set clear boundaries or consider taking a break from the relationship to focus on your healing.\n\n6. **Reflect on the Relationship:** When you're ready, think about what you want moving forward. Understanding your needs and values can guide you in making decisions that are best for your well-being.\n\n7. **Be Patient with Yourself:** Healing takes time, and it's okay to have ups and downs. Give yourself the grace to move forward at your own pace.\n\nRemember, it's perfectly okay to seek help and prioritize your mental and emotional health during this time.",
